SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12307
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract Although legislatures typically use majority rule to allocate a budget in distributive legislation, unanimous consent over the broad allocation of benefits is pervasive. I develop a game-theoretic model where members strategically interact in a universal coalition to determine allocations, with noncooperative bargaining as a threat point for the breakdown of cooperation. To quantify the effects of political power on the agreed-upon allocation, I structurally estimate the model using the ?Bridge Bill Capital Budget? in 1992. I find that 16.73% of the budget would be allocated differently if allocations were determined only based on actual needs.
ER  - 

